{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:46:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:46:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18584"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79767"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11316"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65072"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10353"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79767"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brainstem contains several nuclei that are crucial for maintaining cardiovascular homeostasis through autonomic control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the rostral ventrolateral medulla?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generates sympathetic vasomotor tone","Inhibits cardiac sympathetic outflow","Reduces heart rate","Processes baroreceptor afferent signals","Stimulates parasympathetic activity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egenerates sympathetic vasomotor tone\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the rostral ventrolateral medulla (RVLM). This region contains sympathetic premotor neurones that project to the intermediolateral cell column of the spinal cord to regulate blood pressure and vascular tone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits cardiac sympathetic outflow\u003C/strong\u003E - The RVLM actually increases sympathetic outflow\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses baroreceptor afferent signals\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of the nucleus tractus solitarius\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates parasympathetic activity\u003C/strong\u003E - The RVLM is involved in sympathetic, not parasympathetic, regulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces heart rate\u003C/strong\u003E - The RVLM typically increases heart rate through sympathetic activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe RVLM receives inhibitory input from the caudal ventrolateral medulla and the nucleus tractus solitarius as part of the baroreceptor reflex pathway. This allows for precise control of blood pressure through modulation of sympathetic tone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The nucleus tractus solitarius receives primary afferent input from baroreceptors and chemoreceptors to regulate cardiovascular function.","The rostral ventrolateral medulla contains sympathetic premotor neurones that regulate blood pressure and vascular tone.","The caudal ventrolateral medulla inhibits the rostral ventrolateral medulla to reduce sympathetic outflow."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65072"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65072"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T16:49:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T16:52:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11316"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79767"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-